# Cookbook ŌĆö intent ŌåÆ trait / type

A pattern book for "I need to X" questions. Pick the matching intent,
use the suggested trait / type. When none fits, the correct answer is
usually "add a trait to the ecosystem", not "use a std primitive".

## "I need to return an optional value"

Return `Maybe<T>` (from `notko`). Construct with `Maybe::Is(v)` /
`Maybe::Isnt`. Destructure with pattern match or `?` (needs
`try_trait_v2` feature, nightly).

## "I need a fallible operation"

Return `Outcome<T, E>` (from `notko`). `E` should be a `repr(C)` enum of
well-known failure kinds, not a free-form error type. `?` works via
`try_trait_v2`.

## "I need an infallible value (hot path)"

Return `T` directly, or `Just<T>` when the signature needs explicit
"never fails" framing. `Just<T>` is `#[repr(transparent)]` + `Try` with
`Residual = Infallible` ŌĆö zero cost.

## "I need arithmetic that works for Hot / Warm / Cold / Precise"

Take a trait bound: `<T: UArith<BITS>>` for unsigned,
`<T: IArith<BITS>>` for signed. Caller picks concrete strategy;
monomorphisation generates the right code per call site.

## "I need a bit pattern"

`Mask64` for Ōēż 64 bits, `Mask256` for Ōēż 256, `BitMatrix<N>` for square
grids. All from `arvo-bitmask`.

## "I need bit-level operations"

Take a trait bound from `arvo-bits`: `T: BitSequence + BitAccess` when
the consumer scans bits and reads / writes individual positions; add
`+ BitLogic` when the consumer also needs whole-word OR / AND / NOT /
XOR (or use `core::ops::{BitOr, BitAnd, BitNot, BitXor}` on the `Hot`
containers ŌĆö arvo-bits impls them). Works across `Mask64` / `Mask256`
/ custom storage.

## "I need a sparse matrix"

`arvo_sparse::CsrMatrix<T>`. Iterate via provided accessor; never raw
index into backing storage.

## "I need a bounded integer"

`UFixed<I, F, S>` / `IFixed<I, F, S>` from arvo, parameterised by
integer width `I`, fractional width `F`, and strategy marker `S`.
Semantic aliases (`Mass<S>`, `Angle<S>`, etc.) shadow the raw form.

## "I need to measure size / capacity"

`USize` (not raw `usize`). `Cap` when used as a const-generic capacity.

## "I need a float"

`FastFloat` (Hot: no NaN/Inf guards) or `StrictFloat` (Cold: IEEE
compliant). Never bare `f32` / `f64` in a pub API.

## "I need a predicate-returning function"

Return `Bool` (from `arvo-bits`). `Bool` implements `Try` with
`Residual = Infallible` so `?` extracts the inner `bool` at zero cost.
For `if` expressions use `*val.is_zero()` (Deref) or
`val.is_zero()?`. See
`arvo/docs/ARVO_NEWTYPE-DEREF.md` for the full rationale.

## "I need to iterate a bounded source"

Accept `impl IntoIterator<Item = T>` (lazy) or `&[T]` (concrete slice).
Prefer slice when the caller will always have a slice; iterator when
lazy is an option.

## "I need to emit items from an algorithm (no return-by-value)"

Take `&mut impl Collector<T>` as a parameter. The sink trait lives in
`hilavitkutin-api` once #83 lands; until then, author a local trait for
the use case.

## "I genuinely need std"

Arvo is `#![no_std]`, no alloc, no platform ŌĆö by design. If you think
you need std, the API shape is wrong. File a design round describing
why, then reshape until the std dep disappears.

## Repo-specific additions

| Intent | Type / trait |
|--------|--------------|
| Declare a new numeric semantic alias | `pub type Mass<S: Strategy = Warm> = UFixed<ŌĆ”, ŌĆ”, S>` |
| Declare a new bit-level trait | Add to `arvo-bits` (traits only; no concrete storage) |
| Graph analysis | `arvo-graph` ŌĆö `topo_sort`, `rank_levels`, `waist`, `spanning_tree` |
| Partition a matrix | `arvo-spectral::Laplacian` ŌåÆ `fiedler_partition` ŌåÆ `Mask64` |
| Combinatorial opt | `arvo-comb` ŌĆö DP, greedy grouping, bin packing |

